      "message": "[Critical] Line 201: The backoff retry timer is armed while `mutex` is held, but `expires_at()` cancels any pending wait and Asio may invoke the cancelled handler immediately/inline depending on executor state. That handler locks the same mutex, which can deadlock during re-arm. Avoid calling timer cancellation/re-arm operations while holding `mutex`, or make the handler not take the same lock on cancellation paths. For example, compute the desired retry time under the lock, then arm the timer after releasing it.\n```suggestion\n    std::optional\u003cstd::chrono::steady_clock::time_point\u003e retryAt;\n    {\n        std::unique_lock lock(mutex);\n        ...\n        if (earliestRetry !\u003d std::chrono::steady_clock::time_point {})\n            retryAt \u003d earliestRetry;\n    }\n    if (retryAt)\n        scheduleBackoffRetry(*retryAt);\n```\nThen make `scheduleBackoffRetry()` internally synchronize only its own state carefully.",
